content.description:
The crack immediately right of

Unknown II

is an independent line until the last 15' or so.  The climbing is very different - thin hands at the crux that gradually get bigger until the routes merge.
content.protection: Finger-sized gear and up to #2 or #3 Camalot.
content.location:
It is about 10' right of

Unknown II

.

content.description: Climb the slot with hands to thin hands and finally huge fists before topping out on the pillar at a two cold shut anchor.  Climb overhanging choss for a move into slot.  Climb the slot with good hand jams in back to a good rest/stance.  Continue up thin hands with good feet on the face widening to offwidth to the top of the pillar.
content.protection: #0.75 Camalot through #4 Camalot with doubles to #3. 2 bolt/cold shut anchor.
content.location:
This is left of

Key Hole

about 100 yards, passing a few other bolted routes on the way.  The route is #2 in the beta photo. There is also a left-arching crack visible in the beta photo (#1) with a plaque at the base with name and 5.11 rating.

content.description:
The route to the left of

Unknown II

.  This is the start of "

Make the Grade

", but it has a very different character and its own anchor at the top.
content.protection:
Big stuff - #2 to #5 Camalots.

Per

Sam Jones

: to 2018's #6 Camalots.
content.location: The approach is as casual as it gets in Escalante - a ridge provides an easy hike to the route.

content.description: This is full value, desert crack fun.  Climb a short overhang to OW to grovelling squeeze to reasonable chimney.
content.protection: Big cams, Big Bros to 5, run out 30-40 feet to top.
content.location: It is the huge crack behind enormous detached block to the right of the Interiors Wall area. This is hard to miss.

content.description: Sporty and suprisingly solid Chinle guards the start. Channel your inner bird, and nest some C3s to get you to the goods. It is tips to fingers for 50ish feet. Then journey though varied hands with multiple good rests. This is a really great route.
content.protection:
Purple and green c3 Camalots, 0.3 (2), triples 0.4 - #2, #3 (2), and a #4.

It is a long pitch. A 70m rope got us down with rope to spare. A 60m rope might reach with some stretch (unconfirmed). You could likely get yourself to solid and higher ground just to the left.
content.location:
It is just left (40ish feet) of

Key Hole

.

content.description: Climb up the first 10 feet to the bird shit ledge. Then start the finger and thin hands crack. Watch out for a loose flake. Then the crack opens to perfect hands for a while then hits a lower angle part with a lot more bird shit everywhere.
content.protection: #0.5-#4 Cams. 2 bolt anchor at the top.
content.location: This is at the entrance of cave in the shaded area.

content.description:
The route is relatively short, but fun:

-Short fingers section at start can be stemmed.

-Thin hands all the way to the top.
content.protection:
#1 Metolius through #1 BD.

Anchor:

1 bolt, tattered blue webbing with locking carabiner, 1 welded cold shut.
content.location:
This is on the same leaning block as

Lieback

.

Lieback

is left line, Right of Lieback is the right line.

content.description:
This is one of the few easy desert cracks.  Most of the climbing is on the face to the right.

Per S. Green: ...1st is the 5.6 open book. 2nd is 5.9+ and traverses up right, squeezes through a hole, and finishes atop the cliff.

I don't have a guidebook and don't know the FA information or route name.  I'll be happy to fill these in if provided.
content.protection: A couple of #3.5 (old sizes) Camalots are probably enough if you move them with you.

content.description:
This is the big chimney you walk through to get to the Cave routes. Go up until you can chimney over to the anchors at the top of the

Cave Route

.
content.protection: Big Bros, #4s and #5s or don't bother.
content.location: Start at the entrance to Cave routes.

climbs.name: Not Like Any Other Desert Splitter (Left Dihedral?)

content.description:
This ascends a 35 meter, left-leaning dihedral. It starts up the choss and then goes into the overhanging blocks.

Lots of thin gear is required to tackle this one. The crack is mostly fingers and smaller, and it's totally worth the few feet of loose at the bottom. Stemming, finger locks, tips, chimney, the works. This is a good adventure.
content.protection: Bring lots of thin pieces up to a #6, no #5s, one #4, and 15 draws/slings.
content.location: It is to the right of the Unknowns.

content.description: Climb a few chossy moves, and top out.
content.protection: A pad.
content.location: This is on the cave side trail of Interiors.

content.description: After climbing 20' or so of easy wide crack up a ramp, step up to the plate to the steep, left-arching crack. The crack opens and closes as it goes through many pods. Reaching through these pods often results in good hand jams. Make an awkward last move to clip the chains dangling in space!
content.protection: A #5 and maybe a #6 Camalot for the beginning wideness. Bring singles of #0.5, 0.75, 1, 3 Camalot and doubles of #2.
content.location:
Begin 12 feet to the left of

Unknown II

. The shiny chains hanging in space obviously mark the route.

content.description: This is the crack immediately right of the cave entrance.
content.protection: The crack starts at #1 Camalot and widens to a #5 by the top.  One of each is [adequate] - and extra #3 or #4 helps at the crux.

content.description: This is a short, splitter, hand crack.  Make a few finger moves between pods at the bottom with a short traverse left before climbing straight up thin hands to hands (crux) to a two bolt anchor with chains.
content.protection: #3 TCU up through #2 Camalot.  I used 2 #0.75 Camalots and 2 #3 TCUs, as well as the other recommended gear.
content.location:
This route is located to the left of the

Bunny Ramp

route by about 100 yards.  It is an obvious splitter in white rock that is visible from the parking area.

content.description: This is the route at the far end of the cave, immediately behind the flake.  There are a lot of good rests and this is quite mild for the area.
content.protection: A standard rack up to #3 Camalot will do.

content.description:
The flake on the outside of the cave area, just right from the easy route.

I don't have FA information or route name but will be happy to add them.
content.protection:
I used a Bigbro to protect the start but a good spot is probably sufficient. Above this you'll need a standard rack - nothing unusual.

A modern wide rack of cams will work for the offwidth BD 4-7, then a finger sized piece or two for the top.

content.description:
Start up any of the routes next to

Make the Grade

, and head up the right crack to the anchors. It begins off about 6 inches from the main ledge and then narrows down to 1 inch and then back to 5 inch as you head to the anchor. The rock is good the gear is good, and the climb is fun!
content.protection: The upper half can take a 1 six inch, 2 five inch pieces (one for the bottom and one for the top), and singles from 0.5 to 3 inches.
content.location:
This is to the right of

Make the Grade

.

content.description:
This is a great line a couple corners to climber's right (East) of

Lieback

. All I know about it other than what I know from climbing it has been gleaned from the thread for the photo that depicts the route in the Interiors Wall area section, which I will submit as a photo for this route.

You have to stand on a pile of weird, muddy stuff to start it. Begin with a thin hands/fingers section that is probably best laybacked, which felt 5.10+.

Continue into hands then fists, and turn an overhang/bulge with fists. Continue as the crack widens into #4/#5 size, and turn another overhang in an awkward offwidth section that felt harder, probably the crux of the route at 5.11 something or at least 5.10+.

Finish up the widening offwidth for 10 or 15 feet, and end by traversing left on junk/sandy edges to the bolted anchors. This section was scary and sketchy, a very cool finish to a very cool route. Watch out for loose rock on the sandy ledge above the anchor, and prepare for an extremely uncomfortable belay.

A last comment: I think one could probably take the squeeze chimney above this route to the top of the cliff, but you would need bigger gear.

Descent: this can be rapped with a single 60m rope from the anchors, make sure to tie knots! You will almost reach the ends and will have to swing a bit to climber's left to stand.
content.protection:
Protection: bring everything from purple/green Camalots for the bottom up through #5 for the top, I think it would be nice to have up there although I didn't place one. Bring doubles/triples of hand/fist size for the middle.

Anchors: there are two nice looking bolts with chains in a terrible place to belay.
content.location:
Look at the photo to find this route, it is labeled NEW. This is two corners to climber's right (EAST) of the route

Lieback

. Look up about 100 feet, and you will see two sets of bolted anchors. The ones on the left I presume could be used for the hard-looking corner on the left, and the ones on the right are for this route. Stand on a pile of dried, muddy looking stuff to start the route.

content.description: Climb through a finger crack over some edges. Mount up on the large, detached pillar and start up the corner at the top of the pillar. Once high enough to reach to the right, plug a couple cams into the large flake. Transition through stemming and a layback with a small crimp on the face of the flake. If the crack was not packed with petrified mud, you could jam it, but keep up the layback until you get a hand jam. From here, it is big #3 (3.5 is ideal) through some steep terrain to the chains.
content.protection: Bring a couple small fingers for the bottom. 2 #2s, 1 #2, 3 #3s, a #3.5 or #4 Camalots.
content.location:
This is 20 feet right of

Key Hole

.

content.description: This is a great, varied route that offers some powerful movement as the crack steepens. Be careful of the choss which makes up the first 30' of the route. Climb a section of offwidth, making a transition to the steep roof section that is primarily made up of #4s. Plug and gun your way through to a rest. Finish with a sandy topout.
content.location: This route is a long walk down canyon from main Interiors. The best landmark is the Large house sized boulder below near the road. This boulder is large enough to house one or two routes. Directly above it are a few routes, this being one of them.

content.description: This great route provides a tad bit of nearly every offwidth size. It is a great full body workout. The start is smartly protected by a bolt, then a quick mantel to a pedestal launches you into the meat. Stack, wing, and chimney your way to the top. A few crumbly face holds appear here and there. The crux is exiting the first thirty feet of splitter in to the lightly arching bulge.
content.protection: 2-3 (#4, #5, #6). A Valley Giant 9 was helpful in places.
content.location:
It is approximately a hundred feet up canyon (left) of

Everything in Between

.
